---
import ServicePage from '../../components/ServicePage.astro';

const orgId = new URL('/#organization', Astro.site).href;
const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Service',
    name: 'Music Royalty Accounting & Copyright Administration',
    serviceType: 'Royalty accounting',
    description:
      'Royalty tracking, reconciliation, and copyright administration for artists and songwriters: composition and master royalties verified, discrepancies chased down, mechanical royalties managed for independent releases.',
    provider: { '@id': orgId },
    areaServed: [
      { '@type': 'AdministrativeArea', name: 'Nashville Metropolitan Area' },
      { '@type': 'Country', name: 'United States' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<ServicePage
  title="Music Royalty Accounting | BriBiz"
  description="Royalty tracking, reconciliation, and copyright administration — composition and master royalties verified, discrepancies chased down, mechanicals managed."
  breadcrumbName="Royalty Accounting"
  heroTitle="Royalty Accounting & Copyright Administration"
  schema={schema}
  related={[
    ['Business management', '/services/business-management/'],
    ['Tour accounting', '/services/tour-management/'],
    ['Tax services', '/services/tax-services/'],
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Making money in the music industry has long been called "a river of nickels" –
    sometimes, maybe even pennies. Your song is out in the world, and… what
    happens next? Where does your mailbox money come from? Who collects it, and
    why? That river runs through more hands than most artists realize, and every
    handoff is a place where money can quietly go missing.
  </p>

  <h2>Two Copyrights, Many Checks</h2>
  <p>
    Behind every recording there are basically two copyrights: the Composition –
    the song itself, typically split between songwriters and publishers – and the
    Master, the recording, often owned by a label or an indie artist. Which one
    you own decides which royalties you're due: mechanicals, public performance
    through your PRO, digital performance through SoundExchange, sync fees when
    your music lands in a film or a commercial. Each flows on its own schedule,
    from its own collector, on its own statement.
  </p>
  <p>
    The music business is one of the most complicated payment structures in the
    world. You can have countless streams of revenue with spreadsheets and
    statements galore. You need someone who knows the language, stays up to date,
    and specializes in music revenue administration.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Do With All Of It</h2>
  <p>
    Whenever you receive royalties, we make sure they're correct. We track what
    comes in against what should have come in, and when the numbers don't match,
    we chase down the discrepancies. We've done in-house royalty audits and
    brought in third-party experts to ensure that labels are paying fairly. For
    some clients, we've gone as far as overseeing the sale of a publishing
    catalog.
  </p>
  <p>
    If your album is released independently, we also manage the mechanical
    royalties you owe on the songs you record – so the indie freedom doesn't come
    with a compliance headache attached.
  </p>

  <h2>Want the Map?</h2>
  <p>
    We put together an infographic that traces how royalties actually flow – from
    the radio station, streaming service, or venue, through the collectors, to
    the people who get paid. It's the chart we wish every artist saw before
    signing anything.
  </p>
  <p>
    <a href="/downloads/bribiz-royalties-infographic.pdf">Download the royalties
    infographic (PDF)</a>
  </p>
</ServicePage>
